	public class TopLevel {
	
		public static void main(String[] args) {
			TopLevel topLevel = new TopLevel();
			Nested nested = new TopLevel.Nested();
			Inner inner = topLevel.new Inner();
		}
		
		public static class Nested {
		}
		
		public class Inner {
		}
	}

There are actually 4 distinct syntactic contexts:

  1.  In the &quot;compilation-unit&quot; context; i.e. a top-level class declaration.

          package foo;
          public class Bar{}

  2.  As a nested class declaration in a class declaration.

          package moo;
          public class Cow {
              public class Inner {}
          }


  3.  As a nested class declaration in a method declaration.

          package too;
          public class Far {
              public void test() {
                  class MethodInner{}
              }
          }

  4.  As an anonymous class declaration in a `new` expression.  The expression could appear in a variety of contexts.  For example:

          package goo;
          public class Tar {
              public void test() {
                  Runnable r = new Runnable() {
                      public run() { }
                  };
              }
          }

